    <h1>Follow the Lead</h1>
                    
    <h3 class="c_dblue">The Steps to Successful Floortime</h3>
    <p>
        Floortime encourages communication and thinking while deepening your relationship. Your aim is to create joyful, back and forth communication with your child, building emotional and thinking skills. By responding to your child’s interests, you open a new world for you and your child. Here are explanations of the three basic steps in Floortime which you will see demonstrated in videos shortly. Begin by following your child’s lead.
    </p>


    <h3 class="c_dblue">Following your child’s lead might sound pretty easy.</h3>
    <p>
        Your child decides what to do and you play along. He’s the cop, you’re the robber. She’s the captain of the ship, you’re the crew. Except they may not want you to play; they may have a hard time getting started; they may want to do the same thing over and over.
    </p>

    <div class="sep">

        <h3 class="c_dblue" style="text-align:center;">So how do you <abbr class="vocab"><abbr class="definitionbox"><abbr class="definition">In Floortime, parents and therapists allow the child with autism to take the lead by engaging in preferred activities. It is up to the adults to creatively engage with the child’s interests, even when those interests are unusual.</abbr></abbr><abbr class="term">follow the lead</abbr></abbr>? What lead?</h3>

    </div>

