    <ul class="star_blue_med">

        <li>
            Identify what the child is doing.
            </li>
        <li>
            Make sure the child is calm; if not, soothe first
            </li>
        <li>
            Join the child’s interest and activity (sensory, objects, or words/ideas).
            <br />
            Don’t just watch and comment.
            </li>
        <li>
            Treat the child’s every action (even repetitive motions) as purposeful.
            </li>
        <li>
            Use your voice and facial expressions to become the most interesting object in the room.
            </li>
        <li>
            Respond to your child by raising or lowering your energy level and voice
            </li>
        <li>
            Use language and <abbr class="vocab"><abbr class="definitionbox"><abbr class="definition">Children with autism may or may not have strong verbal skills, but many have the ability to use gestures (movements of the hands, body, or face) to communicate wants, needs, and ideas. Parents and therapists can also use gestures with or without words to open or close circles of communication.</abbr></abbr><abbr class="term">gestures</abbr></abbr> (movements) together
            </li>
        <li>
            Encourage your child, but don’t control his play
            </li>

    </ul>
